d by anthropologists John L. Comaroff and Jean Comaroff, explores the reasons behind the increasingly assertive politics of custom in many corners of Africa. Chiefs come in countless guises—from university professors through cosmopolitan businessmen to subsistence farmers–but, whatever else they do, they are a critical key to understanding the tenacious hold that “traditional” authority enjoys in the late modern world. Together the contributors explore this counterintuitive chapter in Africa’s history and, in so doing, place it within the broader world-making processes of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrica-Politics and government-1960-. 0aChiefdomszAfrica. 0aChiefdoms-Africa. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican politics.  achiefship.  acustomary authority.  apolitical economy.  apolitics of custom.1 aAdrover, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeucher, Benoît, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButhelezi, Mbongiseni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComaroff, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aComaroff, Jean, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aComaroff, John L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aComaroff, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoyle, Lauren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerme, Mariane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo